Unlike their stuffier older sibling, the Nobel Prizes, the Ig Nobel Prizes are a celebration of scientific breakthroughs that “first make people laugh, and then make them think.” Run by the magazine Improbable Research, the annual awards are now in their 31st year — and just as ridiculous as ever. This year’s awards took place via a fever dream-like webcast, as opposed to its usual setting of Harvard University, where real Nobel laureates handed out the 10 prizes. The awards are also, apparently, big in Japan as they were also specifically broadcasted through a Japanese webstream.
​
​Hit this image via the link in our bio to read more about this year's Ig Nobel awards! 🏆

node.text:
The mountain gorilla (Gorilla beringei beringei) is one of the two subspecies of the eastern gorilla. They reach maturity at three and a half years old and can grow to a standing height of 161–171cm and a weight of 120–191kg.

There are two populations: one group lives in Central Africa's Virunga volcanic mountains, which are protected by three national parks: Mgahinga in southwest Uganda, Volcanoes in northwest Rwanda, and Virunga in eastern Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC). Bwindi Impenetrable National Park in Uganda is home to the other population.

Mountain gorilla groups sleep together at night in nests made of foliage on the ground or in trees. Infants will be safe and snug by sharing their mothers' nests.

The IUCN has classed it as endangered as of 2018, with habitat destruction being the greatest threat. Their land is being degraded for agriculture at an increasing rate, and competition for limited natural resources has resulted in deforestation.

Image credit: Papa Bravo / Shutterstock.com

node.text:
The Atlantic puffin (Fratercula arctica), also known as the common puffin, is a seabird found mainly on Iceland's Westman Islands.

Puffins are around 25cm in length and sport a mainly black-and-white plumage with occasional splashes of bright orange. It molts while at sea in the winter, losing some of the color on its face before regaining it in the spring.

These birds spend the majority of their time at sea, resting on the waves like bobbing ducks. They are exceptional swimmers who can dive underwater using their wings to beat through the water, almost as if they are flying.

Their proficient swimming skills mean they can dive to depths of 60m and navigate with rudder-like webbed feet, though they normally only stay below for 20 to 30 seconds. Puffins are remarkably agile flyers in the air, achieving speeds of 55mph by flapping their wings up to 400 times each minute.

Image credit: Jorge Corcuera / Shutterstock.com

node.text:
This is the beautiful rose-red rock of Petra in Jordan. 

Completely natural, Petra’s famously vibrant sandstone is swirled with layers of red, white, pink, yellow, purple and brown, but gives off a mainly rosey-red hue. The sand was deposited by river systems over millions of years and the colored layers of quartz sandstone depend on the minerals they are naturally mixed with. Iron oxide causes the pink and red, dark purple and blue comes from manganese, and yellow from sulfur. 

Sandstone is easily weathered and the rocks, caves, and canyons here have been carved into fantastical shapes like abstract art.
​
​Image credit: Bill Perry / Shutterstock

How do you measure a lion? Carefully, as the old joke goes. It turns out, keepers at ZSL London Zoo are pretty sneaky at cajoling animals onto weighing scales for their annual check-up, utilizing food, treats, and enrichment fun as a means of getting the animals where they need to be. 

Annual check-ups are vital to ensure the animals are happy, healthy, and growing, but also to ensure the Zoo’s info is up to date and accurate as they share it with a worldwide network of zoos to aid in conservation. The annual weigh-in also has an extra function: flagging possible pregnancies. Many of the Zoo’s residents are threatened and part of breeding programs around the world, so knowing about any potential bouncing babies as early as possible is extra important. 

Video credit: @zsllondonzoo

Say hello to the vomer conch, arguably the owner of the greatest googly eyes in the ocean. These sea snails sit in the family Strombidae and are found mainly in tropical and subtropical waters. 

Known to marine science as Euprotomus vomer, these animals spend most of their time burrowed in the sand but will come out at night to feed. Their unusual eyes come in handy when predators are about, stuck on the end of long stalks which can move independently and poke out one at a time to see if the coast is clear.

Cordulagomphus is an extinct genus of dragonflies that lived between 145.5 and 65.5 million years ago during the Cretaceous period. Characteristic features for these dragonflies include four large wings and two long antennae, as well as an elongated tail.

This particular fossil was found in the Santana Formation in Brazil, an Early Cretaceous rock formation that’s proven time and again to house remarkable insect fossils. Scientists have also unearthed pterosaurs, reptiles, amphibians, diverse invertebrates, plants and exceptionally well-preserved fossil fishes.
